                       Tutorial Using AmigaGuide
                       ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

                                       by @{ "M.Meany" link me }

 Introduction
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~
 This tutorial has been written as  an  AmigaGuide  database.  Where you see
gadgets in this text,  click  them  for  more  information.  Use the Retrace
gadget at the top of this page to move back through the path you have taken.

 The tutorial was written using @{ "Platinum Scribble" link scribble} word processor.

 Using TAGs Under Workbench 2+
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 As of WB2, some system library  functions  can  accept a variable number of
entry parameters. This has been implemented using Tag Lists. A Tag is a flag 
that informs a function that a either specific  option is required or that a
specific parameter has been passed.

 Tags are sent to the function as a  list  of LONG words, the address of the
first Tag being the parameter passed.  There  a some Tags that are global to
all functions, such as @{ "TAG_DONE" link tag}, but  for  the most part each functions has
Tags specific to it.

 A Tag Item consists of two long words.  The first is the Tag identifier and
the second is the Tag data. This  is  best  illustrated  by  an example: The
function  @{ "OpenWindowTagList()" link openwindowtag}  accepts  two  parameters,  a  pointer  to  a
NewWindow structure  and  a  pointer  to  a  Tag  List.  The  first of these
parameters is optional and may be set to  NULL, in which case Intuition will
use default values that can be modified by Tag Items in the Tag List:

               suba.l          a0,a0                    no NewWindow
               lea             opentags,a1              a1->Tag list
               CALLINT         OpenWindowTagList
               move.l          d0,MyWindow

               < rest of code >

opentags       WA_Title,WinName
               TAG_DONE

WinName        dc.b            'Marks New Window',0
               even

 Notice in the above fragment that  the  Tag  List consists of just a single
Tag Item. This Tag Item informs the  function  that the windows title should
be set to the string at label WinName.

 The only example included with this whirlwind  tutorial demonstrates use of
the above function using a variety of Tag Lists to open the window. Below is 
an outline of the program that you  can  use  to quickly examine any part of
the source:

@{ "Example1" SYSTEM acc_32:guideeg/example1 }              Test out the example right now!

@{ "Includes" link include}              Include relevant .i files
@{ "Open Libraries" link openlibs}        Open all required libraries
@{ "Close Libraries" link closelibs}       Close all open libraries
@{ "Next Window" link nextwindow}           Code to open and close a window
@{ "Event Loop" link eventloop}            Wait for windows close gadget to be hit
@{ "Window 1" link tag1}              Tag List used to open Window 1
@{ "Window 2" link tag2}              Tag List used to open Window 2
@{ "Window 3" link tag3}              Tag List used to open Window 3
@{ "Window 4" link tag4}              Tag List used to open Window 4
@{ "Window 5" link tag5}              Tag List used to open Window 5

 Now do you see the benefits of AmigaGuide?
 
 						M.Meany

@ENDNODE



